Analyzing the forces on the coupled piston units reveals that the partial pressure of gas B pushing left on the first membrane is exactly balanced by the partial pressure of gas B pushing right on the final rigid boundary sheet. The net force on the connected rod system is zero throughout the transition, meaning zero mechanical work is performed ($W = 0$).
  
  Since the mixing path is isothermal for ideal gas components, internal energy does not alter ($Delta U = 0$). Invoking the first law:
  $ Q = Delta U - W = 0 => Q = T(S_f - S_i) = 0 => S_i = S_f $
  This confirms Gibbs Theorem: the total entropy of an ideal mixture is identical to the sum of individual gas component entropies evaluated as if each component exclusively filled the complete volume alone.